2 VAR Example with 3 Variables: Fed Funds, Real GNP, and Inflation

Using the log differences of each Real GNP and Inflation, the previous method creates lowest frequency series. In this illustrative VAR example from Lutz Kilian1, Fed Funds (monthly) is averaged over 3-period windows to align with quarterly GNP data.

library(vars)

# Load Variables
FF = read.csv("fedfunds.txt",header=FALSE,sep = '\t')

realgnp = read.csv("realgnp.txt",header=FALSE,sep = '\t')
drgdp = diff(log(realgnp[,3]))*100

gnpdeflator = read.csv("gnpdeflator.txt",header=FALSE,sep = '\t')
infl = diff(log(gnpdeflator[,3]))*100

irate = numeric()
for(i in seq(1,length(FF[,3]),3)){
  irate[i] = mean(FF[i:(i+2),3])
}

irate = na.omit(irate)


y = cbind("Diff Real GDP"=drgdp[1:213],"Interest Rate"=irate,"Inflation"=infl[1:213])

2.1 Forecast next 12 Quarters Using All Methods

We will withhold 12 quarters of observations as the test set. Let’s see how accurate a VAR, a random forest and NNS are…

Why a random forest? The Bank of England has recently been posting working papers utilizing machine learning, specifically random forests:

  • Machine Learning at Central Banks

  • Predicting Bank Distress in the UK with Machine Learning

2.1.1 VAR

# Forecast next 12 quarters
h = 12

# Create train and test sets for both versions
y_train = head(y, dim(y)[1] - h)
y_test = tail(y, h)

# 4 quarterly lags used in VAR
VAR_train =  VAR(y = y_train, p = 4)
VAR_test = predict(VAR_train, n.ahead = 12)

par(mfrow=c(1,3))


# Plot predictions and actual values
for(i in 1:3){
  plot(VAR_test$fcst[[i]][,1], tail(y_test[,i],12))
  lines(tail(y_test[,i],12),tail(y_test[,i],12),col='blue')
}

VAR_predictions = cbind(rbind(Diff.Real.GDP=cor(VAR_test$fcst[[1]][,1], tail(y_test[,1],12))^2,
                              Interest.Rate=cor(VAR_test$fcst[[2]][,1], tail(y_test[,2],12))^2,
                              Inflation=cor(VAR_test$fcst[[3]][,1], tail(y_test[,3],12))^2)
                        )

colnames(VAR_predictions) = c("VAR Estimates R2 to Actual Values")

VAR_predictions

The correlations for the VAR forecast of realgdp and inflation versus the actual out-of-sample values were negative!

2.1.2 NNS and Random Forest

2.1.2.1 Function to Generate Lagged Variables

The following code is to generate a matrix of lagged variables to be used in both NNS and Random Forest routines.

lag.fx <- function(x,tau){
  colheads <- NULL

  if(is.null(dim(x)[2])) {
    colheads <- noquote(as.character(deparse(substitute(x))))
    x <- t(t(x))
  }
  
  j.vectors <- list()
  
  for(j in 1:ncol(x)){
      if(is.null(colheads)){
          colheads <- colnames(x)[j]

          colheads <- noquote(as.character(deparse(substitute(colheads))))
      }

      x.vectors <- list()
      heads <- paste0(colheads, ".tau.")
      heads <- gsub('"', '' ,heads)
      
      for (i in 0:tau){
          x.vectors[[paste(heads, i, sep = "")]] <- numeric(0L)
          start <- tau - i + 1
          end <- length(x[,j]) - i
          x.vectors[[i + 1]] <- x[start : end, j]
      }
      
      j.vectors[[j]] <- do.call(cbind,x.vectors)
      colheads <- NULL
  }
  
  return(as.data.frame(do.call(cbind,j.vectors)))
}


# Test it
set.seed(123)
x <- rnorm(10); y <- rnorm(10); z <- rnorm(10)

lag.fx(cbind(x=x,y=y,z=z),3)
# Compare to last values of each variable
tail(x); tail(y); tail(z)

2.1.2.2 Predictions

2.1.2.2.1 1 Year Lag \((\tau = 4)\), 3 Year Forecast \((h = 12)\)
library(randomForest)

tau = 4

y = cbind(lag.fx(cbind(GDP=drgdp,FF=irate,INF=infl),tau))

head(y)
train_l = dim(y)[1] - h
y_train = head(y, train_l)

y_test = tail(y, h)

# Select tau = 0 as DVs
DVs = which(grepl("tau.0", colnames(y)))

for(i in DVs){
  test.set = y_test[,i]
  
# NNS.boost() is an ensemble method comparable to xgboost, and aids in dimension reduction
  nns_boost_est = NNS.boost(y_train[,-i], y_train[,i], IVs.test = y_test[,-i],
                            obj.fn = expression(sum((predicted - actual)^2)), objective = 'min',
                            learner.trials = 100, epochs = 100, ncores = 1, type = NULL)
  
  print(paste0("NNS Boost R2: ", cor(nns_boost_est$results, test.set)^2))
  plot(nns_boost_est$results, test.set)
  lines(test.set, test.set, col = 'orange', lwd = 2)
  
# NNS.stack() cross-validates the parameters of the multivariate NNS.reg() and dimension reduction NNS.reg()
  nns_reg_est = NNS.stack(y_train[,names(nns_boost_est$feature.weights)%in%colnames(y_train)], y_train[,i],
                          IVs.test =  y_test[,names(nns_boost_est$feature.weights)%in%colnames(y_train)])$stack
  
  print(paste0("NNS Regression R2: ", cor(nns_reg_est, test.set)^2))
  plot(nns_reg_est, test.set)
  lines(test.set, test.set, col = 'red', lwd = 2)
  
# Random Forest
  rf = randomForest(y_train[,-i], y_train[,i])
  rf.pred = predict(rf, newdata = y_test[,-i])
  print(paste0("Random Forest R2: ", cor(rf.pred, test.set)^2))
  plot(rf.pred, test.set)
  lines(test.set, test.set, col = 'green', lwd = 2)
}

3 INTERPOLATE THE VALUES OF realgnp and gnpdeflator USING NNS.reg()

Now we will reverse the operations of interpolation to the highest frequency series, the monthly Fed Funds.

Note the final results of the interpolated values versus the original data. Scroll the output table to see all columns…

# Name variable columns for joining
names(FF) = c("Year", "Month", "FF")

names(realgnp) = c("Year", "Month", "realgnp")

names(gnpdeflator) = c("Year", "Month", "gnpdeflator")


# Align quarterly data with corresponding month [1,2,3,4] -> [3,6,9,12]
realgnp[,2] = gnpdeflator[,2]*3
gnpdeflator[,2] = gnpdeflator[,2]*3


# Merge variable data.frames by Year and Month
a = Reduce(function(x,y) merge(x = x, y = y, by = c("Year", "Month"), all = TRUE), 
       list(FF, realgnp, gnpdeflator))

# Create a row index to our reduced data.frame
a = cbind(index = 1:dim(a)[1], a)

# Create subsets of indicies and raw quarterly values
var1 = subset(a, select = c(index, realgnp))
var1 = var1[complete.cases(var1),]

var2 = subset(a, select = c(index, gnpdeflator))
var2 = var2[complete.cases(var2),]

head(var1)
head(var2)
# Use NNS.reg() to interpolate the overall index and raw quarterly values
interpoloted_realgnp = NNS.reg(var1[, 1], var1[, 2],
                               point.est = a$index, order = 'max', plot = FALSE)$Point.est

interpoloted_gnpdeflator = NNS.reg(var2[,1], var2[,2],
                                   point.est = a$index, order = 'max', plot = FALSE)$Point.est

# Combine interpolated values to existing data.frame
b = cbind(a, interpoloted_realgnp, interpoloted_gnpdeflator)

head(b, 12)

4 Use Interpolated Variables

This step creates the new log differenced variables in a data.frame y_new.

drgdp = diff(log(b$interpoloted_realgnp))*100
infl = diff(log(b$interpoloted_gnpdeflator))*100

y_new = cbind("Diff Real GDP" = drgdp,"Interest Rate" = na.omit(b$FF),"Inflation" = infl)

7 Comments

Unlike random forests, NNS has interpretability, albeit less straightforward than the VAR. Furthermore, NNS can extrapolate well beyond observed ranges, whereby random forests cannot. Finally, multivariate partial derivatives can be extracted using the finite step method, which NNS has a routine for, dy.d_ to aid in policy decisions.

This is still a very active area of development, and all questions / comments are welcomed! \ email: fviole@fordham.edu

Thank you for your interest!
